  "doc_id": "7204",
  "text": "We conclude that 8,12-iso-iPF2a-VI isoprostane may be a good marker of the neuropathogenic mechanisms mediating brain injury in konzo. Whether motor and cognition deficits associated with the toxic effects of cyanide share common mechanisms and whether the later are reversible and may run across the lifespan of cassava-reliant populations, has yet to be established. The identification of markers of disease process including concentrations of F2-isoprostanes is, among other important research steps, critical for the development of interventional studies to prevent and/or reverse the neurotoxic effects of cyanogenic cassava. Interventional trials may primarily include methods for proper cassava processing prior to human consumption [CITATION_1] , adoption of balanced diet programs, promotion of neutraceutials i.e. foods with health benefits, as well as supplementation with antioxidants.",
